.TH WATCHTOWER 1 2025-11-20 "WATCHTOWER 0.1.0"
.
.SH NAME
.P
watchtower \- an extension to the watch command
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.
.SY watchtower
[--list|--menu]
.YS
.
.SY watchtower
<script_name|script_file> [<script_argument> ...]
.YS
.
.SY watchtower
--command=arguments <command_argument> ...
.YS
.
.SY watchtower
--command=string <command_string> <command_string_argument> ...
.YS
.
.SY watchtower
--install [--move|--copy|--link] <script_file> ...
.YS
.
.SY watchtower
--edit [--list|--menu] [--copy]
.YS
.
.SY watchtower
--edit <script_name|new_script_name> ...
.YS
.
.SY watchtower
--edit --copy <script_name|script_file> [<new_script_name>]
.YS
.
.SY watchtower
--rename [--list|--menu]
.YS
.
.SY watchtower
--rename <old_script_name> [<new_script_name>]
.YS
.
.SY watchtower
--remove [--list|--menu]
.YS
.
.SY watchtower
--remove <script_name> ...
.YS
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.P
\%\fBwatchtower\fR augments the functionality of the \fBwatch\fR command. It offers a convenient interface to run and manage watch tasks in form of scripts providing easy access to common operations.
.
.SH MODES
.P
Modes are subsets of functionality that either run automatically under certain conditions, or are triggered by passing special option arguments called mode switches. Mode switches are described in this section. See OPTIONS for information on the rest of the option arguments. See NOTES for additional information on command line option usage.
.TP
\%default
Run a \%\fBwatchtower\fR script.
.IP
If no non-option arguments are passed, the list submode is entered. Otherwise, the action submode is entered.
.
.RS
.TP
\%list
List installed scripts. Runs automatically as previously specified, or when an \%\fB--ls,\ --list\f$ or \%\fB--menu\fR mode switch is passed explicitly.
.IP
See also \fBconf_default_submode[\fRlist\fB]\fR.
.RS
.TP
.B \%--ls, --list
List scripts in plain text.
.
.TP
.B \%--menu
List scripts as an interactive menu.
.IP
Requires \fBsmenu\fR to be installed, otherwise falls back on \%\fB--ls,\ --list\fR.
.IP
If a selection is made, continues in action mode.
.RE
.TP
\%action
Run the script.
.RE
.
.TP
.B \%-c[c], --command\fR[={arguments|string}]
Run a specified command. See also \fBconf_default_submode[\fRcommand\fB]\fR.
.
.RS
.TP 9
\%[<default>]
Either 'arguments' or 'string' depending on the value of \%\fBconf_default_submode[command]\fR, which is set to 'arguments' by default.
.TP
\%\fB-c\fR\ / \%arguments
Run a command as passed via positional arguments. See also SYNOPSIS and NON-OPTIONS\~\[->] \%<command_argument>.
.TP
\%\fB-cc\fR\ / \%string
Run a string of Bash code. See also SYNOPSIS and NON-OPTIONS\~\[->] \%<command_string>, \%<command_string_argument>.
.RE
.
.TP
.B \%--install
Install a \%\fBwatchtower\fR script. See also \fBconf_default_submode[\fRinstall\fB]\fR.
.
.RS
.TP
.B \%--mv, --move
Install scripts by moving them to the scripts directory.
.
.TP
.B \%--cp, --copy
Install scripts by copying them to the scripts directory.
.
.TP
.B \%--ln, --link\fR[={{symbolic|hard},{relative|absolute}}]
Install scripts by linking them to the scripts directory. See also \fBconf_default_submode[\fRlink\fB]\fR.
.
.RS
.TP 11
\%symbolic
Create symbolic links. See also \fBconf_default_submode[\fRsymbolic_link\fB]\fR.
.RS
.TP 11
\%relative
Create symbolic links using relative paths.
.TP
\%absolute
Create symbolic links using absolute paths.
.RE
.TP
\%hard
Create hard links.
.RE
.RE
.
.TP
.B \%-e, --edit
Edit installed scripts, or create and edit a new one.
.IP
If no non-option arguments are passed, the list submode is entered. Otherwise, the action submode is entered.
.
.RS
.TP
\%list
Same as MODES\~\[->] \%default\~\[->] \%list.
.IP
Multiple scripts may be selected by pressing \fBT\fR. (Only applies if no \%\fB--cp,\ --copy\fR mode switch is passed.)
.TP
\%action
Edit selected scripts.
.RS
.TP
\%default
Edit an installed script, or create a new one from scratch.
.IP
If a script name is passed that doesn't match any of the installed scripts, a new file with the corresponding name is open for editing.
.TP
.B \%--cp, --copy
Create a new script by creating a copy of an existing one.
.IP
If only one non-option argument is passed, an interactive prompt is shown asking for the new script name.
.RE
.RE
.
.TP
.B \%--rename
Rename an installed script.
.IP
If no non-option arguments are passed, the list submode is entered. Otherwise, the action submode is entered.
.
.RS
.TP
\%list
Same as MODES\~\[->] \%default\~\[->] \%list.
.TP
action
Rename the script.
.IP
If only one non-option argument is passed, an interactive prompt is shown asking for the new script name.
.RE
.
.TP
.B \%--rm, --remove
Delete installed scripts.
.IP
If no non-option arguments are passed, the list submode is entered. Otherwise, the action submode is entered.
.
.RS
.TP
\%list
Same as MODES\~\[->] \%default\~\[->] \%list.
.IP
Multiple scripts may be selected by pressing \fBT\fR.
.TP
action
Delete the scripts.
.RE
.
.SH NON-OPTIONS
.P
This section describes usage of non-option arguments. See SYNOPSIS and MODES for more information on the conditions under which they are used.
.
.TP
\%<script_name>
A name of a \%\fBwatchtower\fR script installed in the scripts directory. See also SCRIPTS and FILES\~\[->] "Scripts".
.IP
The name of the script is derived by taking the script's filename and dropping the '.bash' extension.
.
.TP
\%<script_file>
A path to a \%\fBwatchtower\fR script file located anywhere on the user's system.
.
.TP
\%<script_argument>
A positional argument passed to a \%\fBwatchtower\fR script.
.
.TP
\%<command_argument>
An argument that constitutes a part of a shell command including the very first argument that refers to the command itself.
.
.TP
\%<command_string>
A string of Bash code. This is the same \%\fIcommand_string\fR as the one described in \%\fBbash\fR(1) under OPTIONS\~\[->] \%\fB-c\fR.
.
.TP
\%<command_string_argument>
An argument to Bash's \fIcommand_string\fR. See \%\fBbash\fR(1)\~\[->] OPTIONS\~\[->] \%\fB-c\fR.
.
.TP
\%<old_script_name>
A name of a \%\fBwatchtower\fR script that is to be renamed.
.IP
See also \%<script_name> for the definition of a script name.
.
.TP
\%<new_script_name>
A new name for a \%\fBwatchtower\fR script that is being renamed, or a name for a new \%\fBwatchtower\fR script created by copying an existing one.
.IP
See also \%<script_name> for the definition of a script name.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.P
This section describes usage of option arguments except for mode switches. See MODES for information on mode switches. See NOTES for additional information on command line option usage.
.
.SS General
.
.TP
.B \%--watch
Use the \fBwatch\fR command in default and command modes. This is the default.
.
.TP
.B \%--no-watch
Do not use the \fBwatch\fR command.
.
.TP
.B \%--watch-bin\fR=<empty|bin|path>
A \fBwatch\fR binary to use. The default value is ''.
.IP
When set to an empty string (''), looks up 'watch' on \%\fBPATH\fR. When set to a value that does not contain a forward slash ('/'), looks up that value on \%\fBPATH\fR. When set to a value with a forward slash in it, uses that value as the path to the binary.
.
.TP
.B \%--watch-opts\fR=[:[:]]\%<opt_string>
Options to \%\fBwatch\fR. The default value is described under CONFIGURATION\~\[->] "Command line option equivalents".
.IP
See NOTES\~\[->] "Option strings" for the description of the \%<opt_string> format.
.IP
See also \fBconf_watch_opts\fR.
.
.SS Command execution
.P
These options govern behavior around commands that \%\fBwatchtower\fR executes under the hood.
.
.TP
.B \%-x[x],\ --exec
Execute commands (as opposed to performing a dry run for preview purposes). This is the default.
.
.RS
.TP
.B \%-x
Perform the specified behavior of this option.
.TP
.B \%-xx
In addition to performing the specified behavior of this option, flip the decision value of \%\fB--exec-print\fR.
.RE
.
.TP
.B \%-X[X],\ --no-exec
Do not execute commands. Perform a dry run.
.
.RS
.TP
.B \%-X
Perform the specified behavior of this option.
.TP
.B \%-XX
In addition to performing the specified behavior of this option, flip the decision value of \%\fB--exec-print\fR.
.RE
.
.TP
.B \%--exec-print\fR[={always|auto|never}]
Print commands and their arguments as they are being executed.
.
.RS
.TP 9
[always]
Always print commands.
.TP 9
almost-always
Print commands except in cases where it would be obtrusive. This is the default.
.TP
auto
Print commands only when performing a dry run (\%\fB--no-exec\fR).
.TP
never
Never print commands.
.
.P
\%\fB-xx\fR and \%\fB-XX\fR flip the decision value of this option. If this option is set to \%'auto', the decision is flipped. If this option is set to \%'always' or \%'never', the outcome is the opposite.
.RE
.
.TP
.B \%--exec-no-print\fR
Do not print commands and their arguments as they are being executed. Equivalent to \%\fB--exec-print\fR set to \%'never'.
.
.TP
.B \%-v,\ --exec-verbose
Execute commands verbosely. This is the default.
.
.TP
.B \%-V,\ --exec-no-verbose
Execute commands non-verbosely.
.
.TP
.B \%-y[y],\ --exec-risky\fR[={yes|ask|no}]
Execute commands that merit a user confirmation.
.
.RS
.TP 9
\%\fB-yy\fR\ / \%yes
Execute without asking.
.TP
\%\fB-y\fR\ / \%[ask]
Show a confirmation prompt before executing. This is the default.
.TP
no
Do not execute. Only show an informational message explaining the situation.
.RE
.
.TP
.B \%-Y,\ --exec-no-risky\fR
Do not execute risky commands. Equivalent to \%\fB-y[y],\ --exec-risky\fR set to \%'never'.
.
.SS Other
.
.TP
.B \%--color\fR[={always|auto|never}]
Colorize the output. The default value is 'auto'.
.
.RS
.TP 9
\%always
Always colorize.
.TP
\%[auto]
Colorize if stdout is connected to a terminal.
.TP
\%never
Never colorize.
.RE
.
.TP
.B \%--no-color
Disable colorization of the output. Equivalent to \fB\%-c,\ --color\fR set to 'never'.
.
.TP
.B \%--help
Open the man page.
.
.TP
.B \%--version
Print version information.
.
.TP
.B \%--config\fR[={auto|edit|generate|remove|none}]
Perform an action on the configuration file. See also CONFIGURATION and FILES below.
.
.RS
.TP 9
\%[auto]
Generate a configuration file if it does not exist. If it does, open it in a text editor.
.TP
\%edit
Open an existing configuration file in a text editor.
.TP
\%generate
Generate a new configuration file.
.TP
\%remove
Delete an existing configuration file. If the configuration directory doesn't have any other files, it is also deleted.
.TP
\%none
Do not use the configuration file. Use the program in its default configuration.
.RE
.
.TP
.B \%--no-config
Do not use the configuration file. Use the program in its default configuration. Equivalent to \fB\%--config\fR set to 'none'.
.
.SH SCRIPTS
.P
\%\fBwatchtower\fR scripts are Bash scripts. A \%\fBwatchtower\fR script file must have a '.bash' filename extension.
.P
\%<script_argument>s are passed to \%\fBwatchtower\fR scripts as positional arguments. See SYNOPSIS, \%NON-OPTIONS\~\[->] \%<script_argument>.
.P
An associative array \%\fBWATCHTOWER_SCRIPT\fR is made available to all scripts run by \%\fBwatchtower\fR. Its contents are listed below. See also NOTES\~\[->] "Pseudo data types" for explanation of terms "boolean", "string", "number", etc.
.P
NOTE: Running a \%\fBwatchtower\fR script with the \fB--exec-print\fR option may help better understand how a script's shell context is constructed:
.P
.RS 2
.EX
watchtower --no-exec --exec-print <script_name>
.EE
.RE

.TP
.B \%WATCHTOWER_SCRIPT \fI(associative array)
Data passed along by \%\fBwatchtower\fR to a \%\fBwatchtower\fR script.
.
.RS
.TP 9
.B \%WATCHTOWER_SCRIPT[\fRwatch\fB]\fR \fI(boolean)
Represents whether a script is being run through \%\fBwatch\fR or not.
.IP
Holds a decision value that comes from parsing \%\fBwatchtower\fR's \%\fB--watch\fR\ /\ \%\fB--no-watch\fR options and/or the corresponding configuration variable.
.TP 9
.B \%WATCHTOWER_SCRIPT[\fRcolor\fB]\fR \fI(boolean)
Represents whether a script is being run with colorization enabled or not.
.IP
Holds a decision value that comes from parsing \%\fBwatchtower\fR's \%\fB--color\fR\ /\ \%\fB--no-color\fR options and/or the corresponding configuration variable.
.RE
.
.SH CONFIGURATION
.P
A configuration file can be used to change the default behavior of \%\fBwatchtower\fR.
.P
That configuration file is a Bash script that can be generated by using the \%\fB--config\fR option. It sets a number of variables that correspond to command line options, and some other parameters that can only be set in the configuration file.
.
.P
See also FILES.
.
