Determines the location of the configuration directory. If not set, defaults to \%"$HOME/\:\%.config".
.
.
.SH FILES
.
.SS Configuration
.P
A configuration file can be used to change the default behavior of \%\fBwatchtower\fR.
.P
The configuration file's location is \%"$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/\:\%watchtower/\:\%config.bash".
.P
See also CONFIGURATION, OPTIONS\~\[->] \%\fB--config\fR.
.
.SS Scripts
.P
\%\fBwatchtower\fR scripts are installed to \%"$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/\:\%watchtower/\:\%scripts".
.P
See also SCRIPTS, MODES\~\[->] \%\fB--install\fR.
.
.SH NOTES
.
.SS Options with required and optional arguments
.P
Due to a peculiarity of the \%\fBgetopt\fR option parser, there is a slight difference in how option arguments are parsed depending on whether the option argument is optional or not:
.
.P
.TS
tab(|) nokeep;
l l l .
|Short option|Long option
Required argument|-o <value>|--option <value>
|-o<value>|--option=<value>
Optional argument|-o[<value>]|--option[=<value>]
.TE
.
.P
When an option argument is required, the option and the argument may be passed as two separate command lines arguments (\%\[oq]-o <value>\[cq], \%\[oq]--option <value>\[cq]), or as a single command line argument (\%\[oq]-o[<value>]\[cq], \%\[oq]--option[=<value>]\[cq]).
.P
When an option argument is optional, the option and the argument may only be passed as a single command line argument (\%\[oq]-o[<value>]\[cq], \%\[oq]--option[=<value>]\[cq]).
.P
In this manual, required and optional option arguments are marked as follows:
.
.TP
.B \%-o,\ --option\fR=<value>
This option takes a required argument. No square brackets around \%<value>.
.TP
.B \%-o,\ --option\fR[=<value>]
This option takes an optional argument. \%<value> is enclosed in square brackets.
.
.SS Option strings\fR (\%<opt_string>)
.P
Some options and/or configuration variables may provide the ability to pass an option string to another program. Such values are designated as \%<opt_string> and follow \fBxargs\fR quoting rules:
.P
.TP 3
\[bu]
Single or double quotes may be used:
.IP
.RS 4
.EX
\[aq]quoted value'
"quoted value"
.EE
.RE
.TP 3
\[bu]
Backslash has no special meaning inside quotes:
.IP
.RS 4
.EX
\[aq]literal backslash \\ and some more text'
"literal backslash \\ and some more text"
.EE
.RE
.TP 3
\[bu]
Backslash escapes a quote and itself when used outside quotes:
.IP
.RS 4
.EX
\[aq]literal single quote '\\'' and some more text'
"literal double quote "\\"" and some more text"
\[aq]literal backslash '\\\\' and some more text'
.EE
.RE
.P
When a command line option provides this functionality, it may also provide the ability to either replace the existing \%<opt_string> value or append to it at user's choice.
.P
By "the existing value" we mean either a default value or a value set by the user in a configuration file.
.P
In this manual, such command line options are marked as follows:
.TP
.B \%--command-opts\fR=[:[:]]\%<opt_string>
Options to \%\fBcommand\fR.
.P
Prepending \%<opt_string> with a single colon (':') replaces the existing value, and prepending it with a double colon ('::') appends to it.
.P
Such a command line option may have a corresponding configuration variable (see CONFIGURATION\~\[->] "Command line option equivalents"). For our example option, the variable would most likely be called \%\fBopt_command_opts\fR.
\".P
\"\%\fBopt_command_opts\fR may be implemented in such a way that it can be set to an \%<opt_string> value, to an indexed array that takes option arguments directly, or either:
\".TP
\".B \%opt_command_opts\fR=<opt_string> \fI(string)
\"Options to \%\fBcommand\fR.
\".TP
\".B \%opt_command_opts\fR=(<options>) \fI(indexed array)
\"Options to \%\fBcommand\fR.
\".TP
\".B \%opt_command_opts\fR=\%<opt_string> \fI(string)
\".TQ
\".B \%opt_command_opts\fR=(<options>) \fI(indexed array)
\"Options to \%\fBcommand\fR.
.P
An additional configuration variable may be provided that determines what happens when neither a single colon (':') nor a double colon ('::') is appended to \%<opt_string>. For our example option, that variable would most likely be called \%\fBoptdata__command_opts__append\fR, and would be a \fIboolean\fR value as defined in NOTES\~\[->] "Pseudo data types".
.TP
.B \%optdata__command_opts__append\fR \fI(boolean)
If set to true, append to the existing value of \%\fBopt_command_opts\fR when \fB--command-opts\fR is used without any leading colons (':', '::') in its value.
.P
When \%\fBoptdata__command_opts__append\fR is set to true, \%\fB--command-opts\fR will append to the existing value when no colons are prepended to \%<opt_string>, and when set to false, it will replace the existing value.
\".P
\"Sometimes, configuration\ file-only parameters that take \%<opt_string>s are also implemented. For example:
\".TP
\".B \%conf_command_opts\fR=\%<opt_string> \fI(string)
\"Options to \%\fBcommand\fR.
\".P
\"Any further peculiarities regarding the use of specific command line options and configuration variables that make use of option strings will be noted in the respective sections of this manual.
.
.SS Pseudo data types
.P
In Bash, there is no strict distinction between strings, integers, booleans, and some other data types, but for the sake of clarity of the intended meaning, the configuration variables are marked in terms of these categories.
.P
In the generated configuration file, you will see the values formatted according to the following convention:
.P
Strings are quoted while numeric values are not.
.P
.RS 2
.EX
opt_option='value' # string
opt_option=17      # integer
.EE
.RE
.P
Variables intended as booleans are set to the value of 1 to mean true, and to an empty string to mean false:
.sp
.RS 2
.EX
opt_option=1 # true
opt_option=  # false
.EE
.RE
.
